5|$|On March 11, 2010, <b>Verkhovna</b> <b>Rada</b> of Ukraine {{approved}} {{the structure of}} the Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine. Note, Tihipko even though is a leader of the Strong Ukraine party, he was elected to Cabinet as unaffiliated. Strong Ukraine in <b>Verkhovna</b> <b>Rada</b> is not an independent party. The same goes with Vasyl Tsushko who was {{a former member of the}} Socialist Party of Ukraine at the time of his appointment (he became the leader of that party in July 2010); Tsushko was appointed on quote of the Communist Party.|$|E
5|$|Led by the Party of Regions faction in March 2010 a draft {{law on the}} {{judiciary}} and a new criminal procedural code was shelved {{and the introduction of}} anti-corruption legislation was pushed back from April 2010 to January 2011 by the <b>Verkhovna</b> <b>Rada.</b>|$|E
5|$|On November 30, 2010 Yanukovych vetoed a new {{tax code}} made by the Azarov Government and earlier {{approved}} by the <b>Verkhovna</b> <b>Rada</b> but protested against in rallies across Ukraine (one of the largest protests since the 2004 Orange Revolution). Yanukovych signed a new Tax Code on December 3, 2010.|$|E
